Many experts point out that having cops in schools can often lead to students of color being targeted. And many police officers aren’t trained to interact with students, particularly those with special needs.

A HuffPost investigation revealed at least 143 incidents involving the use of Tasers in schools stretching back to 2011. Officers used the weapons on students as young as 11, some of them for incidents as minor as talking back to an adult.
As cops become a fixture in America’s schools, it’s leading to more officers using Tasers on students. Tasers can cause serious injuries and even death, but their use in schools is poorly documented.

Read more of our investigation: http://huffp.st/m6P1y52 It’s the first in a series on these disturbing incidents where people have been told to “go back.”
Another white man pointed a gun at a Hispanic man, threatening to kill him and his family. The man said he had voted for Trump, and now it was time for the Hispanic man to get out of this country.
A white man hit a Muslim teen in the face, knocking his glasses to the ground. As the teen blindly searched for them, the man told him to get out of America.
A black woman found her car egged and a letter by the front door. “Go back to Africa,” it said, next to a symbol for the Ku Klux Klan.

In suburban Maryland, a constellation of counties near Baltimore and D.C., Smith and Peete were not the only people of color over the last four years to experience the terror of being told to “go back”:

Brandon Higgs, who allegedly shot Smith and attacked his coworker Robert Peete, frequented a white supremacist message board. In leaked chats, Higgs called Dylan Roof “St. Roof” and planned to attend the 2017 Charlottesville “Unite the Right” rally, among other racist messages.

Of perpetrators whose race was known, 90% were white. Of perpetrators whose gender was known, 75% were men. And a staggering 20% of the perpetrators, while targeting their victims, invoked Trump’s name or his campaign slogans.

We found over 300 accounts of these incidents in news articles; 16 in police reports obtained through public records requests; and the rest were tips sent to HuffPost and its media partners in the Documenting Hate project. HuffPost spoke with 80 victims and witnesses.

HuffPost built a separate database to examine what “go back” means in the era of President Donald Trump. We collected 800 reports, occurring over the last four years, in which assailants communicated some variation of “go back” to their victims.

The U.S. does a bad job of tracking hate crimes, so in 2017, @propublica launched Documenting Hate, a database of tips. Almost immediately, HuffPost noticed just how pervasively the statement “go back” is hurled at victims.

Almost a year ago, Elvis Smith woke up to a doctor telling him a bullet had destroyed his right tibia. All he’d done that morning was go to work laying concrete when a white man with a gun showed up shouting, “Go back to Africa.” http://huffp.st/m6P1y52 [Photos: @CherylDiazMeyer]

Even though federal law requires employers to provide mothers with time and space to pump, many women are excluded from the protections. By one estimate, 27.6 million women of child-bearing age are carved out of the law. Read full story by @jamieson: http://huffp.st/qKMLayq.
Ironically, many hospitals — even ones that claim to be "baby friendly" — have broken the law and failed to give women time to pump. http://huffp.st/qKMLayq

A Walmart employee had such difficulty pumping at work that she didn't have enough breast milk for her baby. Her colleagues pooled money to buy her formula she apparently couldn't afford. The Labor Department found that Walmart had violated the nursing mothers law.

In some cases, the hurdles to pumping led women to develop breast infections. A worker at an IHOP was often told "not now" when she needed to pump. She eventually suffered from mastitis, a painful inflammation in the breast. http://huffp.st/qKMLayq

Retailers and restaurants were some of the biggest offenders since they were reluctant to give women even unpaid breaks to pump. Many women said they abandoned breastfeeding entirely because their employers made it so difficult. http://huffp.st/qKMLayq

Employers are required under the law to give women reasonable time and space to pump breast milk to take home. We identified more than 250 cases where employers broke that law, including household names like Walmart, Lowes, McDonald's, IHOP and the U.S. Postal Service.

More women are breastfeeding in the U.S. than ever before, as doctors urge them to feed their babies breast milk exclusively for the first six months. But many American employers make it hard, if not impossible, for women to juggle breastfeeding with work. http://huffp.st/qKMLayq

This is the story of the rise and fall of Mic, a once-promising, much-maligned, very 21st-century news organization.

But the money eventually ran out. Last fall, after Facebook ended a lucrative video deal, Mic was forced to lay off its entire staff in a fire sale to Bustle Digital Group. Bryan Goldberg, BDG’s CEO, later said Mic “had a day of cash left in the bank.

At the same time, employees appreciated Mic for its commitment to diversity and empowering writers. “It was by far the most diverse place I’ve ever worked ― and probably ever will,” said Rameez Tase, a former employee. “As a person of color, I was treated more than fairly.”

In 2016, Altchek described “explosive audience growth” as “central” to Mic’s strategy. Another former employee said it felt like “the analytics team ran the newsroom,” so focused was the strategy on clicks and shares. : Getty Images http://huffp.st/mvczN3Q

But the company’s venture capital backers wanted to see huge returns on their investment — which is nearly impossible for a media company. Mic began heavily relying on Facebook traffic, usually garnered by clickbait-y quick hits and targeted videos.

“The next $10 billion media company will be the one that wins over millennials,” co-founder Chris Altchek said, explaining the site's philosophy. Meanwhile, employees received custom Nikes and Bose speakers while doing work they felt mattered. http://huffp.st/mvczN3Q
In 2014, the venture-backed, millennial-focused news site Mic was thriving. The work was meaningful and the perks, numerous. The company was raising millions in funding and rejecting takeover offers.
